<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_04.gif"><img src="/lotr/gfx/mom/clear.gif" height=35 width=1></td>
<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Can You Supersize That For Me?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.73)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149'>Drew "Player27" Lichtenstein</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1149&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 2, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> *NOTE: This article is pre-Mines of Moria, so no Balrog and what not.*<br />
<br />
Site five is hell. Sure, sites seven through nine have the more devastating game text, but site five is when the fellowship &#8220;crosses the bridge&#8221; over from the relatively safe locations of sites one through four, with their low twilight and sanctuary, to the dash towards the finish line, with absurd amount of twilight and minions waiting in the wings. Of course, as a shadow player, its your job to make that little trek a difficult one. <br />
<br />
Minions come in all shapes and sizes. From the Goblin Runner who acts like nothing more than just a free twilight with legs to The Witch King who waits in the depths of Middle-Earth for his victims, the game is won and lost on the power of the shadow deck. Sure, the fellowship has to be sturdy, but if you can&#8217;t inflict enough damage to your opponent as they move along to the adventure path, your sunk. However, what&#8217;s the most efficient way to do this?<br />
<br />
Almost all minions can be divided into one of three categories: utility (read: small), medium, and large:<br />
<br />
Utility: This is your Goblin Runners and Orc Scouting Bands -- as fighters, they&#8217;re not much of anything, but they further your deck&#8217;s goal by adding twilight, inflicting free wounds, getting out cards you need easier, etc&#8230; Moria and Sauron is full of these (Goblin Scavengers, Goblin Runners, trackers, etc&#8230;) while Nazgul and Uruk-Hai have relatively few.<br />
<br />
Medium: Fairly self-explanatory. Usually costing between three and five twilight, these minions are the ones who you drop down with hopes of inflicting some wounds and softening up the fellowship. The Troll&#8217;s Keyward is a perfect example for this: I&#8217;ll play the Keyward very often even with no Troll simply because for the cost of three you have a strength eight and (most importantly) vitality three minions. What really separates the medium from the utility/small is vitality. High strength, cheap minions with low vitality (like the Uruk Messenger) aren&#8217;t going to be too useful with directed archery being the name of the game. Good examples of medium minions are: Troll&#8217;s Keyward, Troop of Uruk-Hai, Morgul Warden, and Ulaire Nelya.<br />
<br />
Large: Again, very self-explanatory. These are the minions people free. I mean, who doesn&#8217;t cringe when they see that they&#8217;ve added seven twilight at an underground site, knowing that the Cave Troll could come down and make some Hobbit snacks? A large minions normally has vitality of at least three, minimum of at least ten strength, and a fairly hefty twilight cost. The best examples (which almost all players know) are the Cave Troll, Lurtz, The Witch King, and Morgul Hunter (who, in my opinion, is pound for pound better than the Band of the Eye: higher vitality and beats up on big companionships).<br />
<br />
This article isn&#8217;t here to present each culture and their strengths with this minions, its here to try to find a good balance between the three types above, with the largest regard to the large portion. With the exception of certain deck designs (and probably Sauron, since they&#8216;re best damage is in the form of events and conditions), it&#8217;s a generally good rule of thumb to run with at least two-third of your shadow deck be minions. I&#8217;ve seen players run a fifty-fifty split and I&#8217;ve also seen their face turn pretty red when they&#8217;re opponent dashes to site nine with fifteen twilight and all they got is a single minion. Only Moria can sort of get around this due to cards like Host of Thousands and They Are Coming, allowing them to make a single minion two or three. Lets face it: a handful of Lurtz&#8217;s Battle Cries and Savagery to Match Their Numbers is worthless without more than just one Uruk-Hai to play.<br />
<br />
Have you ever looked at deck designs and noticed how a lot of players seem to run a handful of Nazguls (especially Ulaire Nelya and Ulaire Enquea), regardless of what other minions they&#8217;re running? The reason here is probably the most dread word in the shadow player&#8217;s vocabulary: roaming. It&#8217;s the reason why Sauron Orcs are so frustrating to play with and why Lurtz will never see broad side of the Council Courtyard. However, most shadow players seem to make a major mistake during sites two and three: they don&#8217;t play minions at all. Yes, it&#8217;s fairly likely that if your not playing dedicated Nazgul that you&#8217;re unlikely to kill off any companions, but that&#8217;s not the point in the early game. The point in the early game is to set up your hand for mid to late game. One of my favorite combos early on at site two or three when running Moria is Goblin Runner and Moria Scout (another great minion: against 90% of decks he&#8216;s a free strength six/vitality two) with a Scimitar. Yes, most likely one will get leveled by archery and the other will get knocked off by Aragorn, but for the cost of three twilight you&#8217;ve gotten three cards out of your hand that almost pay off their roaming on their own and your also that much closer to digging down into your deck and drawing that Cave Troll that you&#8217;ll need later on.<br />
<br />
However, from site four on (five on for the Uruk-Hai, and six for Sauron, though, they should be using other utility cards to do damage until then) your power hitters (read: more than small annoyances unless your Nazgul) come up to bat. Site four/five is an ideal time to at least kill a companion (or make them have to exert enough so you can ping one off at the sanctuary), and, of course, site seven through nine should be the time your strategy hits the gas pedal into full gear. Some of the best articles on Decktech are about site advantage -- read those to get a much better understand as of why controlling what site comes up, especially for minions, is key to winning.<br />
<br />
Meanwhile, just because site control doesn&#8217;t mean you got the game. Nope, you still have to play these pesky minions to do it. The division between small, medium, and large minions is going to make the difference in the game.<br />
<br />
The biggest double edged sword in the game are large minions. Yeah, OK, they&#8217;re large, no one is going to doubt that. And if they&#8217;re fierce and damage +1 (Cave Troll, Lurtz, Witch King with Blade, etc&#8230;) they&#8217;re going to do some damage. However, players in these last few months are finding them easier and easier to get around. Throw Boromir with Armor in front of them a couple times and watch the Tank survive. Or maybe just exert Legolas/Aragorn enough times to stop them cold before the skirmishing even begins. However, is that so bad? If you throw Boromir in front of Lurtz at site seven twice, he&#8217;s not going to be around much longer when he&#8217;s truly needed at site eight and nine. Go ahead and exhaust Legolas/Aragorn and watch as they try to make the move to their sanctuary at Lorthein and they are buffeted  down by a couple of Scouts. The truth of matter is, yes, big minions are expensive and most of the time they won&#8217;t even hurt enough guys, outside of road bumps like Tharin and Pippin, to truly hurt the fellowship, but if they cause a player to lose these fellowship shields before their trek between site seven to nine, consider it a job well done.<br />
<br />
 However, it&#8217;s still important to not cram your deck full of these larger minions: their high twilight cost can be very anti-productive and, on another note, you most decide what&#8217;s more important to your deck (or, more importantly, the fellowship that your up against): dropping one large minion or two or three smaller ones? If your opponent is running dedicated archery, it&#8217;s probably best to have to give them a larger variety of targets to shoot at then one dedicated one. Against decks that rely heavily on one or two good characters (Gandalf, Aragorn), running a larger minion will cause them to lose some ranks and allow minions later in the game to be able to skirmish their key companions. It&#8217;s probably best to run no more than four, maybe five, of the large minions and then try to get them out around site five or six (in a sixty card draw deck) so they can make it easier for your other minions to attack later on.<br />
<br />
Mid-range minions is where the deck should be the most concentrated on: either drop two or three or drop one with a larger minion so they can take on the &#8220;real&#8221; fellowship after Dwarven and Hobbit shields deal with the primary beast at hand. Again, let me reiterate the most important thing about these mid-ranged minions: vitality, vitality, vitality. With archery being such a major deck design, you shouldn&#8217;t be giving them free shots. While your opponent may still be able to get rid of that Keyward or Troop with Aragorn and Legolas, making one exhaust and/or the other be just a couple wounds from death can almost (key word there is almost) be as efficient as actually just winning a skirmish. I don&#8217;t think any Uruk-Hai deck or dedicated Nazgul deck would feel any regret about using four of the Troop or four Neyla: these guys are almost always useful and once they stop roaming (for Neyla, it&#8217;s never an issue), you have a solid minion who won&#8217;t waste up all your twilight. However, still be careful: a deck can&#8217;t be all mid-ranged minions if simply because it&#8217;s still unlikely you&#8217;ll have enough twilight to drop more than two of them. They&#8217;ll do their damage but you still need more support. In a sixty card draw deck, I&#8217;d suggest using eight.<br />
<br />
Utility minions (or your small little buggers) are basically just that: small. They either take archery shots (if your opponent doesn&#8217;t direct) or makes it easier for your larger minions to come out/do damage. Goblin Runners are a perfect example of this -- they can fit into almost any deck simply because once they stop roaming, they add a twilight, but they also give you a person to take an archery shot, another minion your opponent has to assign against, etc&#8230; That&#8217;s the other key to these smaller minions: even while their usefulness may not extend to skirmishing, their mere presence can be beneficial. Assign a weaker companion to a weak minion so they&#8217;ll live and make a bigger one take a wound or lose your Hobbit or Dwarf shield to a Cave Troll and smack down the Runner? Either way, they lose something, but it forces them into a tighter situation and causes them to have at least think about what to do. This is best used with Sauron where until they reach site six, all they really have is small guys for kamikaze runs. Use these guys to plug up holes in your deck: Runners to add twilight, Scavengers (despite eight strength, one vitality makes them &#8220;small&#8221;) get back weapons, etc&#8230;<br />
<br />
To wrap up and reiterate key points:<br />
<br />
-- Keep a good balance with your minions: some to support you strategy, some medium sized ones to force them to take a couple of wounds, and some bigger ones to smack them down and cause them to lose their defenses so your other minions can do more damage.<br />
<br />
-- Don&#8217;t stock up on too many non-minion cards in your shadow deck. Keep it to the basics: weapons and a few conditions. A plethora of strength bonuses for your minions will clog up your hand -- only use ones which either have a second use (Savagery To Match Their Numbers) or that you can play regardless if you have the right minions or not (Saruman&#8217;s Ambition). A good rule is having a shadow deck with at least two-third minions.<br />
<br />
-- Vitality is key. Sure, Scavengers are nice to pull weapons back and the Uruk Messenger is fairly cheap and can be strong with Snows out, but if they don&#8217;t live long enough to skirmish, they&#8217;re worthless.<br />
<br />
-- Big minions are cool, but don&#8217;t stock up on them. It&#8217;s good to use a few to wear down defenses like Pippin/Tharin, but once your at site seven or eight with archers, it&#8217;s much more preferred to have three medium sized minions than one giant one for Aragorn/Legolas to take down.<br />
<br />
-- Play minions early on. Yes, roaming will most likely mean that if your not playing Nazgul that your not likely to get enough early on to do damage, but cards out of your hand are cards drawn.<br />
<br />
-- Just be smart. Don&#8217;t forget that an Orc Ambusher can take archery wounds with the best of them and cause your opponent to at least think through the skirmish phase.<br />
<br />
In conclusion, minions are the beating heart to every deck. If you get them to work, you can wear down the fellowship and eventually pick them off one by one (or just in one massive onslaught). If they don&#8217;t work, you&#8217;ve handed your opponent a victory. Boils down to a fairly easy decision, wouldn&#8217;t you agree?<br />
<br />
-Telek <br />
